# pyenv
#   For a library or package, you might want to ignore these files since the Python version is usually managed by the user.
#   For a software application, you may want to commit .python-version to standardize across development environments.
# .python-version

# pipenv
#   According to pypa/pipenv#598, it's recommended to include Pipfile.lock in version control.
#   However, in case of collaboration, if having platform-specific dependencies or dependencies
#   having no cross-platform support, pipenv may install dependencies that don't work, or even
#   fail to install them. In that case, the lock file should be added to .gitignore.
#Pipfile.lock

# poetry
#   Similar to Pipenv, see https://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-pyprojecttoml-and-poetrylock-to-version-control
#poetry.lock

